# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: common-lisp
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:common-lisp/cl-cookbook-clos-p01] CLOS is the “Common Lisp Object System”, arguably one of the most powerful object systems available in any language.
[src:common-lisp/cl-cookbook-clos-p01] The functionality belonging to this name was added to the Common Lisp language between the publication of Steele’s first edition of “Common Lisp, the Language” in 1984 and the formalization of the language as an ANSI standard ten years later.
[src:common-lisp/cl-cookbook-clos-p01] This page aims to give a good understanding of how to use CLOS, but only a brief introduction to the MOP.
[src:common-lisp/cl-cookbook-clos-p01] Let’s dive in with an example showing class definition, creation of objects, slot access, methods specialized for a given class, and inheritance.
[src:common-lisp/cl-cookbook-clos-p01] The macro used for defining new data types in CLOS is `defclass`.
[src:common-lisp/cl-cookbook-clos-p01] This gives us a CLOS type (or class) called `person` and two slots, named `name` and `lisper`.
[src:common-lisp/cl-cookbook-clos-p01] So, our `person` class doesn’t explicitly inherit from another class (it gets the empty parentheses `()`).
[src:common-lisp/cl-cookbook-clos-p01] However it still inherits by default from the class `t` and from `standard-object`.
[src:common-lisp/cl-cookbook-clos-p01] or even without slot specifiers: `(defclass point () ())`.
[src:common-lisp/cl-cookbook-clos-p01] This has the direct advantage that you can control the required arguments.
[src:common-lisp/cl-cookbook-clos-p01] You should now export the constructor from your package and not the class itself.
[src:common-lisp/cl-cookbook-clos-p01] The function to access any slot anytime is `(slot-value <object> <slot-name>)`.
[src:common-lisp/cl-cookbook-clos-p01] If you don’t specify any of these, you can still use `slot-value`.
[src:common-lisp/cl-cookbook-clos-p01] You can give a slot more than one `:accessor`, `:reader` or `:initarg`.
[src:common-lisp/cl-cookbook-clos-p01] 1- `with-slots` allows to abbreviate several calls to slot-value.
[src:common-lisp/cl-cookbook-clos-p01] The first argument is a list of slot names.
[src:common-lisp/cl-cookbook-clos-p01] The second argument evaluates to a CLOS instance.
[src:common-lisp/cl-cookbook-clos-p01] This is followed by optional declarations and an implicit `progn`.
[src:common-lisp/cl-cookbook-clos-p01] Lexically during the evaluation of the body, an access to any of these names as a variable is equivalent to accessing the corresponding slot of the instance with `slot-value`.
[src:common-lisp/cl-cookbook-clos-p01] 2- `with-accessors` is equivalent, but instead of a list of slots it takes a list of accessor functions.
[src:common-lisp/cl-cookbook-clos-p01] Any reference to the variable inside the macro is equivalent to a call to the accessor function.
[src:common-lisp/cl-cookbook-clos-p01] `:allocation` specifies whether this slot is *local* or *shared*.
[src:common-lisp/cl-cookbook-clos-p01] In the following example, note how changing the value of the class slot `species` of `p2` affects all instances of the class (whether or not those instances exist yet).
[src:common-lisp/cl-cookbook-clos-p01] Each slot accepts one `:documentation` option.
[src:common-lisp/cl-cookbook-clos-p01] To obtain its documentation via `documentation`, you need to obtain the slot object.
[src:common-lisp/cl-cookbook-clos-p01] This can be done compatibly using a library such as closer-mop.
[src:common-lisp/cl-cookbook-clos-p01] Note however that generally it may be better to document slot accessors instead, as a popular viewpoint is that slots are implementation details and not part of the public interface.
[src:common-lisp/cl-cookbook-clos-p01] The `:type` slot option may not do the job you expect it does.
[src:common-lisp/cl-cookbook-clos-p01] If you are new to the CLOS, we suggest you skip this section and use your own constructors to manually check slot types.
[src:common-lisp/cl-cookbook-clos-p01] Indeed, whether slot types are being checked or not is undefined.
[src:common-lisp/cl-cookbook-clos-p01] Clozure CL does it, SBCL does it since its version 1.5.9 (November, 2019) or when safety is high (`(declaim (optimise safety))`).
[src:common-lisp/cl-cookbook-clos-p01] To do it otherwise, see this Stack-Overflow answer, and see also quid-pro-quo, a contract programming library.
[src:common-lisp/cl-cookbook-clos-p01] Note: this is your first introduction to the MOP.
[src:common-lisp/cl-cookbook-clos-p01] The object `my-point` is an instance of the class named `point`, and the class named `point` is itself an instance of the class named `standard-class`.
[src:common-lisp/cl-cookbook-clos-p01] We say that the class named `standard-class` is the *metaclass* (i.e. the class of the class) of `my-point`.
[src:common-lisp/cl-cookbook-clos-p01] We can make good uses of metaclasses, as we’ll see later.
[src:common-lisp/cl-cookbook-clos-p01] As illustrated above, `child` is a subclass of `person`.
[src:common-lisp/cl-cookbook-clos-p01] All objects inherit from the class `standard-object` and `t`.
[src:common-lisp/cl-cookbook-clos-p01] Every child instance is also an instance of `person`.
[src:common-lisp/cl-cookbook-clos-p01] The closer-mop library is *the* portable way to do CLOS/MOP operations.
[src:common-lisp/cl-cookbook-clos-p01] A subclass inherits all of its parents’ slots, and it can override any of their slot options.
[src:common-lisp/cl-cookbook-clos-p01] Common Lisp makes this process dynamic, great for REPL session, and we can even control parts of it (like, do something when a given slot is removed/updated/added, etc).
[src:common-lisp/cl-cookbook-clos-p01] We can further inspect our classes with `class-direct-[subclasses, slots, default-initargs]` and many more functions.
[src:common-lisp/cl-cookbook-clos-p01] Last but not least, be warned that inheritance is fairly easy to misuse, and multiple inheritance is multiply so, so please take a little care.
[src:common-lisp/cl-cookbook-clos-p01] Ask yourself whether `foo` really wants to inherit from `bar`, or whether instances of `foo` want a slot containing a `bar`.
[src:common-lisp/cl-cookbook-clos-p01] A good general guide is that if `foo` and `bar` are “same sort of thing” then it’s correct to mix them together by inheritance, but if they’re really separate concepts then you should use slots to keep them apart.
[src:common-lisp/cl-cookbook-clos-p01] The first class on the list of parent classes is the most specific one, `child`’s slots will take precedence over the `person`’s.
[src:common-lisp/cl-cookbook-clos-p01] Note that both `child` and `person` have to be defined prior to defining `baby` in this example.
[src:common-lisp/cl-cookbook-clos-p01] Suffice it to say that everything’s configurable by implementing methods exposed by the MOP.
[src:common-lisp/cl-cookbook-clos-p01] To redefine a class, simply evaluate a new `defclass` form.
[src:common-lisp/cl-cookbook-clos-p01] This then takes the place of the old definition, the existing class object is updated, and **all instances of the class** (and, recursively, its subclasses) **are lazily updated to reflect the new definition**.
[src:common-lisp/cl-cookbook-clos-p01] You don’t have to recompile anything other than the new `defclass`, nor to invalidate any of your objects.
[src:common-lisp/cl-cookbook-clos-p01] Think about it for a second: this is awesome !
[src:common-lisp/cl-cookbook-clos-p01] In the above example, I became a `child`, and I inherited the `can-walk-p` slot, which is true by default.
[src:common-lisp/cl-cookbook-clos-p01] What if we want to show more information ?
[src:common-lisp/cl-cookbook-clos-p01] `print-unreadable-object` prints the `#<...>`, that says to the reader that this object can not be read back in.
[src:common-lisp/cl-cookbook-clos-p01] Its `:type t` argument asks to print the object-type prefix, that is, `PERSON`.
[src:common-lisp/cl-cookbook-clos-p01] Caution: trying to access a slot that is not bound by default will lead to an error.
[src:common-lisp/cl-cookbook-clos-p01] Where we approach that we don’t need CLOS objects to use CLOS.
[src:common-lisp/cl-cookbook-clos-p01] We see here that symbols are instances of the system class `symbol`.
[src:common-lisp/cl-cookbook-clos-p01] This is one of 75 cases in which the language requires a class to exist with the same name as the corresponding lisp type.
[src:common-lisp/cl-cookbook-clos-p01] Many of these cases are concerned with CLOS itself (for example, the correspondence between the type `standard-class` and the CLOS class of that name) or with the condition system (which might or might not be built using CLOS classes in any given implementation).
[src:common-lisp/cl-cookbook-clos-p01] Note that not all “traditional” lisp types are included in this list.
[src:common-lisp/cl-cookbook-clos-p01] Just as every lisp object is of type `t`, every lisp object is also a member of the class named `t`.
[src:common-lisp/cl-cookbook-clos-p01] This is a simple example of membership of more then one class at a time, and it brings into question the issue of *inheritance*, which we will consider in some detail later.
[src:common-lisp/cl-cookbook-clos-p01] The metaclass of a `structure-object` is the class `structure-class`.
[src:common-lisp/cl-cookbook-clos-p01] It is implementation-dependent whether the metaclass of a “traditional” lisp object is `standard-class`, `structure-class`, or `built-in-class`.
[src:common-lisp/cl-cookbook-clos-p01] `built-in-class`: May not use `make-instance`, may not use `slot-value`, may not use `defclass` to modify, may not create subclasses.
[src:common-lisp/cl-cookbook-clos-p01] `structure-class`: May not use `make-instance`, might work with `slot-value` (implementation-dependent).
[src:common-lisp/cl-cookbook-clos-p01] Use `defstruct` to subclass application structure types.
[src:common-lisp/cl-cookbook-clos-p01] Consequences of modifying an existing `structure-class` are undefined: full recompilation may be necessary.
[src:common-lisp/cl-cookbook-clos-p01] `standard-class`: None of these restrictions.
[src:common-lisp/cl-cookbook-clos-p01] We already saw some introspection functions.
[src:common-lisp/cl-cookbook-clos-p01] Your best option is to discover the closer-mop library and to keep the CLOS & MOP specifications at hand.
[src:common-lisp/cl-cookbook-clos-p01] Below we create methods, we specialize them, we use method combination (before, after, around), and qualifiers.
[src:common-lisp/cl-cookbook-clos-p01] A `generic function` is a lisp function which is associated with a set of methods and dispatches them when it’s invoked.
[src:common-lisp/cl-cookbook-clos-p01] All the methods with the same function name belong to the same generic function.
[src:common-lisp/cl-cookbook-clos-p01] The `defmethod` form is similar to a `defun`.
[src:common-lisp/cl-cookbook-clos-p01] It associates a body of code with a function name, but that body may only be executed if the types of the arguments match the pattern declared by the lambda list.
[src:common-lisp/cl-cookbook-clos-p01] They can have optional, keyword and `&rest` arguments.
[src:common-lisp/cl-cookbook-clos-p01] The `defgeneric` form defines the generic function.
[src:common-lisp/cl-cookbook-clos-p01] If we write a `defmethod` without a corresponding `defgeneric`, a generic function is automatically created (see examples).
[src:common-lisp/cl-cookbook-clos-p01] It is generally a good idea to write the `defgeneric`s.
[src:common-lisp/cl-cookbook-clos-p01] We can add a default implementation and even some documentation.
[src:common-lisp/cl-cookbook-clos-p01] This method can take any argument, it is always applicable.
[src:common-lisp/cl-cookbook-clos-p01] The variable `foo` is bound to the corresponding argument value, as usual.
[src:common-lisp/cl-cookbook-clos-p01] In this case, the variable `foo` is bound to the corresponding argument only if that argument is of specializer class `person` *or a subclass*, like `child` (indeed, a “child” is also a “person”).
[src:common-lisp/cl-cookbook-clos-p01] If any argument fails to match its specializer then the method is not *applicable* and it cannot be executed with those arguments.We’ll get an error message like “there is no applicable method for the generic function xxx when called with arguments yyy”.
[src:common-lisp/cl-cookbook-clos-p01] In place of a simple symbol (`:soup`), the eql specializer can be any lisp form.
[src:common-lisp/cl-cookbook-clos-p01] It is evaluated at the same time of the defmethod.
[src:common-lisp/cl-cookbook-clos-p01] You can define any number of methods with the same function name but with different specializers, as long as the form of the lambda list is *congruent* with the shape of the generic function.
[src:common-lisp/cl-cookbook-clos-p01] The system chooses the most *specific* applicable method and executes its body.
[src:common-lisp/cl-cookbook-clos-p01] The most specific method is the one whose specializers are nearest to the head of the `class-precedence-list` of the argument (classes on the left of the lambda list are more specific).
[src:common-lisp/cl-cookbook-clos-p01] A method with specializers is more specific to one without any.
[src:common-lisp/cl-cookbook-clos-p01] Multimethods explicitly specialize more than one of the generic function’s required parameters.
[src:common-lisp/cl-cookbook-clos-p01] They don’t belong to a particular class.
[src:common-lisp/cl-cookbook-clos-p01] Meaning, we don’t have to decide on the class that would be best to host this method, as we might have to in other languages.
[src:common-lisp/cl-cookbook-clos-p01] In Lisp, we can define `setf` counterparts of functions or methods.
[src:common-lisp/cl-cookbook-clos-p01] We might want this to have more control on how to update an object.
[src:common-lisp/cl-cookbook-clos-p01] If you know Python, this behaviour is provided by the `@property` decorator.
[src:common-lisp/cl-cookbook-clos-p01] When a generic function is invoked, the application cannot directly invoke a method.
[src:common-lisp/cl-cookbook-clos-p01] During the execution of a method, the remaining applicable methods are still accessible, via the *local function* `call-next-method`.
[src:common-lisp/cl-cookbook-clos-p01] This function has lexical scope within the body of a method but indefinite extent.
[src:common-lisp/cl-cookbook-clos-p01] It invokes the next most specific method, and returns whatever value that method returned.
[src:common-lisp/cl-cookbook-clos-p01] Calling `call-next-method` when there is no next method signals an error.
[src:common-lisp/cl-cookbook-clos-p01] You can find out whether a next method exists by calling the local function `next-method-p` (which also has has lexical scope and indefinite extent).
[src:common-lisp/cl-cookbook-clos-p01] Note finally that the body of every method establishes a block with the same name as the method’s generic function.
[src:common-lisp/cl-cookbook-clos-p01] If you `return-from` that name you are exiting the current method, not the call to the enclosing generic function.
[src:common-lisp/cl-cookbook-clos-p01] They are wrappers around the core mechanism we just described.
[src:common-lisp/cl-cookbook-clos-p01] They can be useful to catch return values or to set up an environment around the primary method (set up a catch, a lock, timing an execution,…).
[src:common-lisp/cl-cookbook-clos-p01] If the dispatch mechanism finds an around-method, it calls it and returns its result.
[src:common-lisp/cl-cookbook-clos-p01] If the around-method has a `call-next-method`, it calls the next most applicable around-method.
[src:common-lisp/cl-cookbook-clos-p01] It is only when we reach the primary method that we start calling the before and after-methods.
[src:common-lisp/cl-cookbook-clos-p01] Think of it as an onion, with all the `:around` methods in the outermost layer, `:before` and `:after` methods in the middle layer, and primary methods on the inside.
[src:common-lisp/cl-cookbook-clos-p01] The default method combination type we just saw is named `standard`, but other method combination types are available, and no need to say that you can define your own.
[src:common-lisp/cl-cookbook-clos-p01] You notice that these types are named after a lisp operator.
[src:common-lisp/cl-cookbook-clos-p01] Indeed, what they do is they define a framework that combines the applicable primary methods inside a call to the lisp operator of that name.
[src:common-lisp/cl-cookbook-clos-p01] Here, unlike the standard mechanism, all the primary methods applicable for a given object are called, the most specific first.
[src:common-lisp/cl-cookbook-clos-p01] Similarly, using the `list` type is equivalent to returning the list of the values of the methods.
[src:common-lisp/cl-cookbook-clos-p01] Note that these operators don’t support `before`, `after` and `around` methods (indeed, there is no room for them anymore).
[src:common-lisp/cl-cookbook-clos-p01] They do support around methods, where `call-next-method` is allowed, but they don’t support calling `call-next-method` in the primary methods (it would indeed be redundant since all primary methods are called, or clunky to *not* call one).
[src:common-lisp/cl-cookbook-clos-p01] CLOS allows us to define a new operator as a method combination type, be it a lisp function, macro or special form.
[src:common-lisp/cl-cookbook-clos-p01] We’ll let you refer to the books if you feel the need.
[src:common-lisp/cl-cookbook-clos-p01] It is possible to trace the method combination, but this is implementation dependent.
[src:common-lisp/cl-cookbook-clos-p01] In SBCL, we can use `(trace foo :methods t)`.
[src:common-lisp/cl-cookbook-clos-p01] See this post by an SBCL core developer.
[src:common-lisp/cl-cookbook-clos-p01] There is a difference between declaring methods inside a `defgeneric` body or by writing multiple `defmethod`s: the two methods handle re-definition of methods differently.
[src:common-lisp/cl-cookbook-clos-p01] `defgeneric` will delete methods that are not in its body anymore.
[src:common-lisp/cl-cookbook-clos-p01] You can try them with `(goodbye (make-instance 'person :name "you"))`.
[src:common-lisp/cl-cookbook-clos-p01] Now, later in your work session, you decide that you don’t need the one specializing on `child` any more.
[src:common-lisp/cl-cookbook-clos-p01] But **the method still exists in the image**.
[src:common-lisp/cl-cookbook-clos-p01] You have to programmatically remove the method, see below.
[src:common-lisp/cl-cookbook-clos-p01] Had you used `defgeneric`, all the methods would have been updated, added or deleted.
[src:common-lisp/cl-cookbook-clos-p01] It works for any object type, a person or a child.
[src:common-lisp/cl-cookbook-clos-p01] Try it on a string: `(tidy "tidy what?")`, it works.
[src:common-lisp/cl-cookbook-clos-p01] This might or might not be important to you during development, but knowing this can help you keep your lisp image in sync with your source code.
[src:common-lisp/cl-cookbook-clos-p01] Otherwise, you can remove an old method when it gets on your way.
[src:common-lisp/cl-cookbook-clos-p01] `find-method` takes as arguments: a function reference, a qualifier (like before, after or around), and a list of class specializers.
[src:common-lisp/cl-cookbook-clos-p01] Once you found the method, use `remove-method`.
[src:common-lisp/cl-cookbook-clos-p01] You could use `(fmakunbound 'goodbye)`, but this makes *all* methods unbound.
[src:common-lisp/cl-cookbook-clos-p02] We gather here some examples that make use of the framework provided by the meta-object protocol, the configurable object system that rules Lisp’s object system.
[src:common-lisp/cl-cookbook-clos-p02] We touch advanced concepts so, new reader, don’t worry: you don’t need to understand this section to start using the Common Lisp Object System.
[src:common-lisp/cl-cookbook-clos-p02] We won’t explain much about the MOP here, but hopefully sufficiently to make you see its possibilities or to help you understand how some CL libraries are built.
[src:common-lisp/cl-cookbook-clos-p02] We invite you to read the books referenced in the introduction.
[src:common-lisp/cl-cookbook-clos-p02] Metaclasses are needed to control the behaviour of other classes.
[src:common-lisp/cl-cookbook-clos-p02] But we’ll change it to one of our own, so that we’ll be able to **count the creation of instances**.
[src:common-lisp/cl-cookbook-clos-p02] This same mechanism could be used to auto increment the primary key of a database system (this is how the Postmodern or Mito libraries do), to log the creation of objects, etc.
[src:common-lisp/cl-cookbook-clos-p02] The `:metaclass` class option can appear only once.
[src:common-lisp/cl-cookbook-clos-p02] Actually you should have gotten a message asking to implement `validate-superclass`.
[src:common-lisp/cl-cookbook-clos-p02] See that an `:after` qualifier is the safest choice, we let the standard method run as usual and return a new instance.
[src:common-lisp/cl-cookbook-clos-p02] The `&key` is necessary, remember that `make-instance` is given initargs.
[src:common-lisp/cl-cookbook-clos-p02] To further control the creation of object instances, we can specialize the method `initialize-instance`.
[src:common-lisp/cl-cookbook-clos-p02] It is called by `make-instance`, just after a new instance was created but wasn’t initialized yet with the default initargs and initforms.
[src:common-lisp/cl-cookbook-clos-p02] It is recommended (Keene) to create an after method, since creating a primary method would prevent slots’ initialization.
[src:common-lisp/cl-cookbook-clos-p02] A typical example would be to validate the initial values.
[src:common-lisp/cl-cookbook-clos-p02] We are prompted into the interactive debugger and we are given a choice of restarts (continue, retry, abort).
[src:common-lisp/cl-cookbook-clos-p02] So while we’re at it, here’s an assertion that uses the debugger features to offer to change “name”.
[src:common-lisp/cl-cookbook-clos-p02] The CLOS implementation of `make-instance` is in two stages: allocate the new object, and then pass it along with all the `make-instance` keyword arguments, to the generic function `initialize-instance`.
[src:common-lisp/cl-cookbook-clos-p02] Implementors and application writers define `:after` methods on `initialize-instance`, to initialize the slots of the instance.
[src:common-lisp/cl-cookbook-clos-p02] The system-supplied primary method does this with regard to (a) `:initform` and `:initarg` values supplied with the class was defined and (b) the keywords passed through from `make-instance`.
[src:common-lisp/cl-cookbook-clos-p02] Other methods can extend this behaviour as they see fit.
[src:common-lisp/cl-cookbook-clos-p02] For example, they might accept an additional keyword which invokes a database access to fill certain slots.
[src:common-lisp/cl-cookbook-clos-p02] Suppose you created a “circle” class, with coordinates and a diameter.
[src:common-lisp/cl-cookbook-clos-p02] Later on, you decide to replace the diameter by a radius.
[src:common-lisp/cl-cookbook-clos-p02] You want all the existing objects to be cleverly updated: the radius should have the diameter value, divided by 2.
[src:common-lisp/cl-cookbook-clos-p02] Use `update-instance-for-redefined-class`.
[src:common-lisp/cl-cookbook-clos-p02] Nothing happens yet, you don’t see the output of our “plist values” print.
[src:common-lisp/cl-cookbook-clos-p02] Inspect or `describe` the object: now it will be updated, and you’ll find the `radius` slot.
[src:common-lisp/cl-cookbook-clos-p02] See more on the HyperSpec or on the Community Spec.
[src:common-lisp/cl-cookbook-clos-p02] Now imagine you are working with the `circle` class, but you realize you only need a `surface` kind of objects.
[src:common-lisp/cl-cookbook-clos-p02] You will discard the circle class altogether, but you want your existing objects to be updated -to this new class, and compute new slots intelligently.
[src:common-lisp/cl-cookbook-clos-p02] Use `update-instance-for-different-class`.
[src:common-lisp/cl-cookbook-clos-p02] You want to check if a method exists with a given set of *qualifiers* (such as the `:around` method) and, most importantly, *specializers* (the type(s) the method dispatches on.
[src:common-lisp/cl-cookbook-clos-p02] Now, in our program that uses some introspection, we want to see if such a function exists, and get a reference to it.
[src:common-lisp/cl-cookbook-clos-p02] The first argument, `nil`, is a list of qualifiers.
[src:common-lisp/cl-cookbook-clos-p02] We are not interested in the `:around`, `:before` or `:after` methods, so we keep it `nil`.
[src:common-lisp/cl-cookbook-clos-p02] The second argument is a list of the method’s arguments’ types.
[src:common-lisp/cl-cookbook-clos-p02] `print-object` takes 2 arguments, a person and a stream.
[src:common-lisp/cl-cookbook-clos-p02] We can use `'(t t)` to get a reference to the generic function.
[src:common-lisp/cl-cookbook-clos-p02] We use `'(person t)` to get a reference to the method that specializes on a person, and on any stream.
