[src:common-lisp/common-lisp-p02] Common Lisp is used to develop research applications (often in Artificial Intelligence), for rapid development of prototypes or for deployed applications.
[src:common-lisp/common-lisp-p02] Common Lisp is used in many commercial applications, including the Yahoo!
[src:common-lisp/common-lisp-p02] Store web-commerce site, which originally involved Paul Graham and was later rewritten in C++ and Perl.
[src:common-lisp/data-structures-p01] We hope to give here a clear reference of the common data structures.
[src:common-lisp/data-structures-p01] To really learn the language, you should take the time to read other resources.
[src:common-lisp/data-structures-p01] Don’t miss the appendix and when you need more data structures, have a look at the awesome-cl list and Quickdocs.
[src:common-lisp/data-structures-p01] but there are more constructors, and you should also know that lists are made of `cons` cells.
[src:common-lisp/data-structures-p01] The list basic element is the cons cell.
[src:common-lisp/data-structures-p01] We build lists by assembling cons cells.
[src:common-lisp/data-structures-p01] See that the representation is not a dotted pair ?
[src:common-lisp/data-structures-p01] The Lisp printer understands the convention.
[src:common-lisp/data-structures-p01] which is shorthand notation for the function call `(quote (1 2))`.
[src:common-lisp/data-structures-p01] A cons cell car or cdr can refer to other objects, including itself or other cells in the same list.
[src:common-lisp/data-structures-p01] They can therefore be used to define self-referential structures such as circular lists.
[src:common-lisp/data-structures-p01] The list-length function recognises circular lists, returning `nil`.
[src:common-lisp/data-structures-p01] The reader can also create circular lists, using Sharpsign Equal-Sign notation.
[src:common-lisp/data-structures-p01] An object (like a list) can be prefixed with `#n=` where `n` is an unsigned decimal integer (one or more digits).
[src:common-lisp/data-structures-p01] Note that the label given to the reader (`n=42`) is discarded after reading, and the printer defines a new label (`n=1`).
[src:common-lisp/data-structures-p01] We can assign *any* new value with `setf`.
[src:common-lisp/data-structures-p01] return the last cons cell in a list (or the nth last cons cells).
[src:common-lisp/data-structures-p01] `reverse` and `nreverse` return a new sequence.
[src:common-lisp/data-structures-p01] The N stands for **non-consing**, meaning it doesn’t need to allocate any new cons cells.
[src:common-lisp/data-structures-p01] `push` prepends *item* to the list that is stored in *place*, stores the resulting list in *place*, and returns the list.
[src:common-lisp/data-structures-p01] `pushnew` is similar, but it does nothing if the element already exists in the place.
[src:common-lisp/data-structures-p01] See also `adjoin` below that doesn’t modify the target list.
[src:common-lisp/data-structures-p01] `push` is equivalent to `(setf place (cons item place ))` except that the subforms of *place* are evaluated only once, and *item* is evaluated before *place*.
[src:common-lisp/data-structures-p01] There is no built-in function to **add to the end of a list**.
[src:common-lisp/data-structures-p01] It is a more costly operation (have to traverse the whole list).
[src:common-lisp/data-structures-p01] So if you need to do this: either consider using another data structure, either just `reverse` your list when needed.
[src:common-lisp/data-structures-p01] `pushnew` accepts key arguments: `:key`, `:test`, `:test-not`.
[src:common-lisp/data-structures-p01] Use this if `first`, `second` and the rest up to `tenth` are not enough.
[src:common-lisp/data-structures-p01] They make sense when applied to lists containing other lists.
[src:common-lisp/data-structures-p01] This macro does simple pattern matching on lists.
[src:common-lisp/data-structures-p01] From a declaration of parameters, it binds each parameter to its value taken from the input list.
[src:common-lisp/data-structures-p01] We can destructure lists and nested lists, with a fixed or a variable number of elements, we can provide defaults to absent elements, and we can match the keys of property lists, using the lambla list keywords we know from a `defun` or a `defmacro`: `&key`, `&rest`, `&allow-other-keys`, etc.
[src:common-lisp/data-structures-p01] On this example we want to match exactly `(x y z)`, so the list we match on must provide x, y and z.
[src:common-lisp/data-structures-p01] Below we make the presence of `z` optional.
[src:common-lisp/data-structures-p01] We can bind the variable number of elements to `z` with `&rest`.
[src:common-lisp/data-structures-p01] The `&whole` parameter is bound to the whole list.
[src:common-lisp/data-structures-p01] Another useful feature is destructuring a plist, a list alternating a keyword and a value.
[src:common-lisp/data-structures-p01] A destructuring lambda list can contain all the same keywords as a macro lambda list, except for `&environment`.
[src:common-lisp/data-structures-p01] `destructuring-bind`’s structure is: a lambda-list, an input list, an optional declaration using `declare`, one or many forms in the body.
[src:common-lisp/data-structures-p01] If this gives you the will to do pattern matching, see pattern matching.
[src:common-lisp/data-structures-p01] `null` is equivalent to `not`, but considered better style.
[src:common-lisp/data-structures-p01] `listp` tests whether an object is a list or nil.
[src:common-lisp/data-structures-p01] `consp` tests wether an object is a cons cell.
[src:common-lisp/data-structures-p01] The empty list is *not* a cons, so `(consp nil)` is falsy, while `(listp nil)` is truthy.
[src:common-lisp/data-structures-p01] `atom` checks if its argument is an atom, in other words, if it isn’t a `cons`.
