[src:common-lisp/data-structures-p01] searches for an element in the sequence whose `second` element equals 42, rather than for an element which equals 42 itself.
[src:common-lisp/data-structures-p01] If `:key` is omitted or nil, the filter is effectively the `identity` function.
[src:common-lisp/data-structures-p01] You can use a `lambda` function or any function that accepts one argument.
[src:common-lisp/data-structures-p01] `every, notevery (test, sequence)`: they return nil or t, respectively, as soon as one test on any set of the corresponding elements of sequences returns nil.
[src:common-lisp/data-structures-p01] `some`, `notany` *(test, sequence)*: they return either the value of the test, or nil.
