[src:common-lisp/data-structures-p01] The following shows how to create an array that can be pushed to and popped from arbitrarily, growing its storage capacity as needed.
[src:common-lisp/data-structures-p01] This is roughly equivalent to a `list` in Python, an `ArrayList` in Java, or a `vector<T>` in C++ – though note that elements are not erased when they’re popped.
[src:common-lisp/data-structures-p01] If you’re mapping over it, see the `map` function whose first parameter is the result type.
[src:common-lisp/data-structures-p01] Hash Tables are a powerful data structure, associating keys with values in a very efficient way.
[src:common-lisp/data-structures-p01] Hash Tables are often preferred over association lists whenever performance is an issue, but they introduce a little overhead that makes assoc lists better if there are only a few key-value pairs to maintain.
[src:common-lisp/data-structures-p01] Hash Tables are created using the function `make-hash-table`.
[src:common-lisp/data-structures-p01] Its most used optional keyword argument is `:test`, specifying the function used to test the equality of keys.
[src:common-lisp/data-structures-p01] If you want to add an element to a hash table, you can use `gethash`, the function to retrieve elements from the hash table, in conjunction with `setf`.
[src:common-lisp/data-structures-p01] The function `gethash` takes two required arguments: a key and a hash table.
[src:common-lisp/data-structures-p01] It returns two values: the value corresponding to the key in the hash table (or `nil` if not found), and a boolean indicating whether the key was found in the table.
[src:common-lisp/data-structures-p01] That second value is necessary since `nil` is a valid value in a key-value pair, so getting `nil` as first value from `gethash` does not necessarily mean that the key was not found in the table.
[src:common-lisp/data-structures-p01] The Alexandria library (in Quicklisp) has the functions `hash-table-keys` and `hash-table-values` for that.
[src:common-lisp/data-structures-p01] Use `equalp` to compare the equality of hash-tables, element by element.
[src:common-lisp/data-structures-p01] `equalp` is case-insensitive for strings.
[src:common-lisp/data-structures-p01] The first value returned by `gethash` is the object in the hash table that’s associated with the key you provided as an argument to `gethash` or `nil` if no value exists for this key.
[src:common-lisp/data-structures-p01] This value can act as a generalized boolean if you want to test for the presence of keys.
[src:common-lisp/data-structures-p01] But note that this does *not* work if `nil` is amongst the values that you want to store in the hash.
[src:common-lisp/data-structures-p01] In this case you’ll have to check the *second* return value of `gethash` which will always return `nil` if no value is found and T otherwise.
[src:common-lisp/data-structures-p01] Both the key and its associated value will be removed from the hash table.
[src:common-lisp/data-structures-p01] `remhash` returns T if there was such an entry, `nil` otherwise.
[src:common-lisp/data-structures-p01] This will remove all of the data from the hash table and return the deleted table.
[src:common-lisp/data-structures-p01] No need to use your fingers - Common Lisp has a built-in function to do it for you: `hash-table-count`.
[src:common-lisp/data-structures-p01] It is very tempting to use `print-object`.
[src:common-lisp/data-structures-p01] It works under several implementations, but this method is actually not portable.
[src:common-lisp/data-structures-p01] The standard doesn’t permit to do so, so this is undefined behaviour.
[src:common-lisp/data-structures-p01] The Serapeum library has the `dict` constructor, the function `pretty-print-hash-table` and the `toggle-pretty-print-hash-table` switch, all which do *not* use `print-object` under the hood.
[src:common-lisp/data-structures-p01] This printed representation can be read back in.
[src:common-lisp/data-structures-p01] The standard hash-table in Common Lisp is not thread-safe.
[src:common-lisp/data-structures-p01] That means that simple access operations can be interrupted in the middle and return a wrong result.
[src:common-lisp/data-structures-p01] Implementations offer different solutions.
[src:common-lisp/data-structures-p01] With **SBCL**, we can create thread-safe hash tables with the `:synchronized` keyword to `make-hash-table`: http://www.sbcl.org/manual/#Hash-Table-Extensions.
[src:common-lisp/data-structures-p01] In **LispWorks**, hash-tables are thread-safe by default.
[src:common-lisp/data-structures-p01] But likewise, there is no guarantee of atomicity *between* access operations, so we can use with-hash-table-locked.
[src:common-lisp/data-structures-p01] Ultimately, you might like what the **cl-gserver library** proposes.
[src:common-lisp/data-structures-p01] It offers helper functions around hash-tables and its actors/agent system to allow thread-safety.
[src:common-lisp/data-structures-p01] They also maintain the order of updates and reads.
[src:common-lisp/data-structures-p01] The `make-hash-table` function has a couple of optional parameters which control the initial size of your hash table and how it’ll grow if it needs to grow.
[src:common-lisp/data-structures-p01] This can be an important performance issue if you’re working with large hash tables.
[src:common-lisp/data-structures-p01] The values for `hash-table-size` and `hash-table-rehash-size` are implementation-dependent.
[src:common-lisp/data-structures-p01] In our case, CMUCL chooses and initial size of 65, and it will increase the size of the hash by 50 percent whenever it needs to grow.
[src:common-lisp/data-structures-p01] The hash has to be re-sized 19 times until it’s big enough to hold 100,000 entries.
[src:common-lisp/data-structures-p01] That explains why we saw a lot of consing and why it took rather long to fill the hash table.
[src:common-lisp/data-structures-p01] It also explains why the second run was much faster - the hash table already had the correct size.
[src:common-lisp/data-structures-p01] And there was no consing involved because we didn’t have to re-size at all.
[src:common-lisp/data-structures-p01] If we don’t know the final size in advance but can guess the growth behaviour of our hash table we can also provide this value to `make-hash-table`.
[src:common-lisp/data-structures-p01] We can provide an integer to specify absolute growth or a float to specify relative growth.
[src:common-lisp/data-structures-p01] Also rather fast (we only needed one re-size) but much more consing because almost the whole hash table (minus 65 initial elements) had to be built during the loop.
[src:common-lisp/data-structures-p01] Note that you can also specify the `rehash-threshold` while creating a new hash table.
[src:common-lisp/data-structures-p01] An association list is a list of cons cells.
[src:common-lisp/data-structures-p01] Keep in mind that using quote doesn’t evaluate the expressions inside it.
[src:common-lisp/data-structures-p01] To get a key, we have `assoc` (use `:test 'equal` when your keys are strings, as usual).
[src:common-lisp/data-structures-p01] It returns the whole cons cell, so you may want to use `cdr` or `rest` to get the value, or even `assoc-value list key` from `Alexandria`.
[src:common-lisp/data-structures-p01] If the alist has repeating (duplicate) keys, you can use `remove-if-not`, for example, to retrieve all of them.
[src:common-lisp/data-structures-p02] A property list is simply a list that alternates a key, a value, and so on, where its keys are keywords or symbols.
[src:common-lisp/data-structures-p02] A plist is a key-value store, like hash-tables.
[src:common-lisp/data-structures-p02] The keys could be any other object, but if they are not comparable by `eq` (the lowest-level equality function), like strings (that are comparable with `equal` or `string-equal`), you won’t be able to get them back with `getf`.
[src:common-lisp/data-structures-p02] To be more precise, a plist first has a cons cell whose `car` is the key, whose `cdr` points to the following cons cell whose `car` is the value.
[src:common-lisp/data-structures-p02] In the example above, we used keywords for the keys: `:foo`, `:bar`.
[src:common-lisp/data-structures-p02] This is just the most common way to define the keys.
[src:common-lisp/data-structures-p02] You can use quoted symbols instead: `'foo`, `'bar`, but it’s just less conventional.
[src:common-lisp/data-structures-p02] Remember that if you use symbols for keys, then when you’ll want to access those keys from another package, you’ll need to use the fully-qualified symbol name.
[src:common-lisp/data-structures-p02] However, all keywords live in the same package so they always evaluate to themselves.
[src:common-lisp/data-structures-p02] Remember that we can’t set a `:test` keyword to `getf`.
[src:common-lisp/data-structures-p02] Keys must be *identical* by `eq` for `getf` to get you the key.
[src:common-lisp/data-structures-p02] To add elements to a plist, you can use `list*` and `append`, which are *not* destructive.
[src:common-lisp/data-structures-p02] They don’t modify the original plist in place.
[src:common-lisp/data-structures-p02] Use `(setf my-plist (append …))` if you want to change the plist.
[src:common-lisp/data-structures-p02] You can of course `setf` a place you got with `getf`.
[src:common-lisp/data-structures-p02] Structures offer a way to store data in named slots.
[src:common-lisp/data-structures-p02] Classes provided by the Common Lisp Object System (CLOS) are more flexible however structures may offer better performance (see for example the SBCL manual).
[src:common-lisp/data-structures-p02] At creation slots are optional and default to `nil`.
[src:common-lisp/data-structures-p02] note that printed representations can be read back by the reader.
[src:common-lisp/data-structures-p02] We can set the structure’s constructor so as to create the structure without using keyword arguments, which can be more convenient sometimes.
[src:common-lisp/data-structures-p02] we then also have `person-age` and `person-id`.
[src:common-lisp/data-structures-p02] Note that the CLOS object system is more powerful.
[src:common-lisp/data-structures-p02] Here the math involved in the `move-ship` function is easier to read than if accessor functions were used.
[src:common-lisp/data-structures-p02] In this function all the accessors are not too hard to read, but with more complex operations it would quickly get cluttered.
[src:common-lisp/data-structures-p02] Though it is not mentioned in the standard, many modern implementations of Common Lisp permit the use of the CLOS macro `with-slots` with structures.
[src:common-lisp/data-structures-p02] In the standard `with-slots` itself is defined using `symbol-macrolet`.
[src:common-lisp/data-structures-p02] After a change, instances are not updated.
[src:common-lisp/data-structures-p02] If we try to add a slot (`email` below), we have the choice to lose all instances, or to continue using the new definition of `person`.
[src:common-lisp/data-structures-p02] But the effects of redefining a structure are undefined by the standard, so it is best to re-compile and re-run the changed code.
[src:common-lisp/data-structures-p02] There is also very little introspection.
[src:common-lisp/data-structures-p02] Portable Common Lisp does not define ways of finding out defined super/sub-structures nor what slots a structure has.
[src:common-lisp/data-structures-p02] The Common Lisp Object System (which came after into the language) doesn’t have such limitations.
[src:common-lisp/data-structures-p02] A tree can be built with lists of lists.
[src:common-lisp/data-structures-p02] The functions `tree-equal` and `copy-tree` descend recursively into the car and the cdr of the cons cells they visit.
[src:common-lisp/data-structures-p02] See the functions `subst` and `sublis` above to replace elements in a tree.
[src:common-lisp/data-structures-p02] You may want to have a look at the **FSet** library (in Quicklisp) and its excellent documentation to use immutable data structures.
[src:common-lisp/data-structures-p02] You can start reading its excellent documentation that includes a high level conceptual background, a tutorial, an API reference and a comparison with functional data structures from other ecosystems.
[src:common-lisp/data-structures-p02] Another fast, purely functional data structure library for Common Lisp is Sycamore.
[src:common-lisp/data-structures-p02] Use `*print-length*` and `*print-level*`.
[src:common-lisp/data-structures-p02] If you have a very big list, printing it on the REPL or in a stacktrace can take a long time and bring your editor or even your server down.
[src:common-lisp/data-structures-p02] `*print-length*` will be applied at each level.
[src:common-lisp/data-structures-p02] A destructive function alters the argument(s) it was given.
[src:common-lisp/data-structures-p02] How do you know which functions are destructive?
[src:common-lisp/data-structures-p02] The solutions presented below might help you getting started, but keep in mind that they’ll have a performance impact and that error messages will be less explicit.
[src:common-lisp/data-structures-p02] Sometimes we work with nested data structures, and we might want an easier way to access a nested element than intricated “getf” and “assoc” and all.
[src:common-lisp/data-structures-p02] Also, we might want to just be returned a `nil` when an intermediary key doesn’t exist.
[src:common-lisp/data-structures-p02] The `access` library given above provides this, with `(accesses var key1 key2…)`.
[src:common-lisp/functions] Creating named functions is done with the `defun` keyword.
[src:common-lisp/functions] The return value is the value returned by the last expression of the body (see below for more).
[src:common-lisp/functions] The `print` function prints its one argument to standard output *and returns it*. “hello world!” is thus the returned value of our function.
[src:common-lisp/functions] Optional arguments are declared after the `&optional` keyword in the lambda list.
[src:common-lisp/functions] They are ordered, they must appear one after another.
[src:common-lisp/functions] It is not always convenient to remember the order of the arguments.
[src:common-lisp/functions] It is thus possible to supply arguments by name: we declare them using `&key argname`, we set them with `:argname "value"` in the function call, and we use `argname` as a regular variable in the function body.
[src:common-lisp/functions] It is generally a style warning, but it is possible.
[src:common-lisp/functions] You can skip this tip for now if you want, but come back later to it as it can turn handy.
[src:common-lisp/functions] We saw that a default key parameter is `nil` by default (`(defun hello (name &key happy) …)`).
[src:common-lisp/functions] But how can be distinguish between “the value is NIL by default” and “the user wants it to be NIL”?
[src:common-lisp/functions] where `happy-p` serves as a *predicate* variable (using `-p` is only a convention, give it the name you want) to know if the key was supplied.
[src:common-lisp/functions] So now, we will print a sad face if `:happy` was explicitely set to NIL.
[src:common-lisp/functions] Sometimes you want a function to accept a variable number of arguments.
[src:common-lisp/functions] Use `&rest <variable>`, where `<variable>` will be a list.
[src:common-lisp/functions] We might need `&allow-other-keys` when passing around arguments or with higher level manipulation of functions.
[src:common-lisp/functions] We define a function to open a file that always uses `:if-exists :supersede`, but still passes any other keys to the `open` function.
[src:common-lisp/functions] In the case of a duplicated `:if-exists` argument, our first one takes precedence.
[src:common-lisp/functions] The return value of the function is the value returned by the last executed form of the body.
[src:common-lisp/functions] There are ways for non-local exits (`return-from <function name> <value>`), but they are usually not needed.
[src:common-lisp/functions] Common Lisp has also the concept of multiple return values.
[src:common-lisp/functions] Returning multiple values is **not** like returning a list of results.
[src:common-lisp/functions] We didn’t ask to capture the remaining values, so `:b` and `:c` were discarded.
[src:common-lisp/functions] This is actually very handy: you can change a function to return more multiple values than it did, and you don’t need to change and refactor the call sites.
[src:common-lisp/functions] Calling `values` with no arguments returns no value at all.
[src:common-lisp/functions] While most Common Lisp forms return a single value, it is sometimes useful for a function to return several (or none).
[src:common-lisp/functions] Most of the time you only need the rounded value, but if for some reason you want to know the remainder, it can be captured.
[src:common-lisp/functions] If you expect all the values calculated by a function to be used most of the time, then it is better to bundle up the results in a list, a CLOS instance, *etc.,* and return that.
[src:common-lisp/functions] Only use multiple values when the first values are most often needed, and the later ones less often used.
[src:common-lisp/functions] Similarly, getting the content of a hash-table returns two values: the result, and a boolean saying if the key was found or not.
[src:common-lisp/functions] It acts as a `let` binding: the values `c` and `d` exist in the scope of `multiple-value-bind`.
[src:common-lisp/functions] The number of values returned does not have to match the number of variables to bind.
[src:common-lisp/functions] A typical use for multiple values is to distinguish between finding `nil` and a lookup failure.
[src:common-lisp/functions] For example, `gethash` returns two values.
[src:common-lisp/functions] The first is the result of the lookup, which might be `nil` if nothing is found, but could be an actual `nil` stored in the hashtable.
[src:common-lisp/functions] We can call a lambda with `funcall` or `apply` (see below).
[src:common-lisp/functions] There is one thing to keep in mind with `apply`, it is that we can’t use it with super-large lists: the argument list of functions have a length limit.
[src:common-lisp/functions] We can find this limit in the variable `call-arguments-limit`.
[src:common-lisp/functions] While it is rather large on SBCL (4611686018427387903), we have another option to apply a function with arguments of arbitrary length: `reduce`.
[src:common-lisp/functions] `reduce` is used to apply functions on lists and vectors of arbitrary length.
[src:common-lisp/functions] It repeateadly calls the function with two arguments and walks over the argument list.
[src:common-lisp/functions] If our argument was 1000 elements long, `apply` would call the `min` function with 1000 arguments, while `reduce` would call `min` (nearly) a 1000 times with 2 arguments each time.
[src:common-lisp/functions] where `key`, `from-end`, `start` and `end` are key arguments found in other built-in functions (see our data-structures chapter).
[src:common-lisp/functions] If given, `:initial-value` is placed before the first subsequence.
[src:common-lisp/functions] In the example above, we used `#'`, but a single quote also works, and we can encounter it in the wild.
[src:common-lisp/functions] It is generally safer to use `#'`, because it respects lexical scope.
[src:common-lisp/functions] Using `function` or the `#'` shorthand allows us to refer to local functions.
[src:common-lisp/functions] If we pass instead a symbol to `funcall`, what is called is always the function named by that symbol in the *global environment*.
[src:common-lisp/functions] In addition, `#'` catches the function by value.
[src:common-lisp/functions] If the function is redefined, bindings that refered to this function by `#'` will still run its original behaviour.
[src:common-lisp/functions] The behaviour you want depends on your use case.
[src:common-lisp/functions] Generally, using sharpsign-quote is less surprising.
[src:common-lisp/functions] But if you are running a tight loop and you want live-update mechanisms (think a game or live visualisations), you might want to use a single quote so that your loop picks up the user’s new function definition.
[src:common-lisp/functions] Here we have defined the function `adder` which returns an *object* of *type* `function`.
[src:common-lisp/functions] Indeed, CL has different *namespaces* for functions and variables, i.e. the same *name* can refer to different things depending on its position in a form that’s evaluated.
[src:common-lisp/functions] To simplify a bit, you can think of each symbol in CL having (at least) two “cells” in which information is stored.
[src:common-lisp/functions] One cell - sometimes referred to as its *value cell* - can hold a value that is *bound* to this symbol, and you can use `boundp` to test whether the symbol is bound to a value (in the global environment).
[src:common-lisp/functions] You can access the value cell of a symbol with `symbol-value`.
[src:common-lisp/functions] The other cell - sometimes referred to as its *function cell* - can hold the definition of the symbol’s (global) function binding.
[src:common-lisp/functions] In this case, the symbol is said to be *fbound* to this definition.
[src:common-lisp/functions] You can use `fboundp` to test whether a symbol is fbound.
[src:common-lisp/functions] You can access the function cell of a symbol (in the global environment) with `symbol-function`.
[src:common-lisp/functions] Now, if a *symbol* is evaluated, it is treated as a *variable* in that its value cell is returned (just `foo`).
[src:common-lisp/functions] If a *compound form*, i.e. a *cons*, is evaluated and its *car* is a symbol, then the function cell of this symbol is used (as in `(foo 3)`).
[src:common-lisp/functions] In Common Lisp, as opposed to Scheme, it is *not* possible that the car of the compound form to be evaluated is an arbitrary form.
[src:common-lisp/functions] If it is not a symbol, it *must* be a *lambda expression*, which looks like `(lambda lambda-list form*)`.
[src:common-lisp/functions] This explains the error message we got above - `(adder 3)` is neither a symbol nor a lambda expression.
[src:common-lisp/functions] Read the CLHS section about form evaluation for more.
[src:common-lisp/functions] Closures allow you to capture lexical bindings.
[src:common-lisp/functions] This can be useful to store state that you don’t want to have to keep passing into your function(s), either as a convenience or to keep state variables out of a reachable namespace.
[src:common-lisp/functions] In addition to counter generators, another common use of lexical closures is memoization — caching previous results of functions that are expensive to calculate.
[src:common-lisp/functions] Using the non-memoized Fibonacci function below quickly gets quite time-consuting to calculate.
[src:common-lisp/functions] Using a hash table to store previously calculated results can speed things up.
[src:common-lisp/functions] We could use a `defvar`, but this is a good use case for a closure since that avoids adding a variable only used by one function to the namespace.
[src:common-lisp/functions] There are several memoization libraries, some of which wrap this lexical closure and caching mechanics up in a macro.
[src:common-lisp/functions] This mechanism is often used for CLOS methods.
[src:common-lisp/functions] Let’s say we manipulate a hash-table that represents a square.
[src:common-lisp/functions] During our program life cycle, we can change the square width, with `setf` as we did above.
[src:common-lisp/functions] We define a function to compute a square area.
[src:common-lisp/functions] We don’t store it in the hash-table as it is redundant with the dimension.
[src:common-lisp/functions] Now, our programming needs lead to the situation where it would be very handy to change the `*area*` of the square… and have this reflected on the square’s dimensions.
[src:common-lisp/functions] and check your square (`describe`, `inspect`…), the new width was set.
[src:common-lisp/functions] Note that setf-functions only have one mandatory argument, the new value.
[src:common-lisp/functions] The second and other arguments are optional.
[src:common-lisp/functions] This setf-function sets a global parameter (`*current-buffer*`) to the new value.
[src:common-lisp/functions] A related concept is that of *currying* which you might be familiar with if you’re coming from a functional language.
[src:common-lisp/functions] Now that you know how to do it, you may appreciate using the implementation of the Alexandria library (in Quicklisp).
[src:common-lisp/getting-started] We’ll begin by presenting easy steps to install a development environment and to start a new Common Lisp project.
[src:common-lisp/getting-started] Common Lisp is an ANSI standard but implementations can vary greatly in what they provide in addition to the standard.
[src:common-lisp/getting-started] See Wikipedia’s list of implementations.
[src:common-lisp/getting-started] You can also install the Emacs editor with Homebrew, but it isn’t *required* to use Common Lisp.
