[src:common-lisp/getting-started] SBCL is available on Chocolatey, albeit this is *not* an official installation method.
[src:common-lisp/getting-started] You can also use plain-common-lisp, a trivial way to get a native Common Lisp environment on Windows.
[src:common-lisp/getting-started] It lets you install Emacs with Slime, Quicklisp and SBCL in a couple clicks: you only have to extract its archive in your workspace.
[src:common-lisp/getting-started] If you already know Docker, you can get started with Common Lisp pretty quickly.
[src:common-lisp/getting-started] The clfoundation/cl-devel image comes with recent versions of SBCL, CCL, ECL and ABCL, plus Quicklisp installed in the home (`/home/cl`), so than we can `ql:quickload` libraries straight away.
[src:common-lisp/getting-started] Docker works on GNU/Linux, Mac and Windows.
[src:common-lisp/getting-started] We still want to develop using Emacs and SLIME, so we need to connect SLIME to the Lisp inside Docker.
[src:common-lisp/getting-started] See slime-docker, which is a library that helps on setting that up.
[src:common-lisp/getting-started] The asdf-vm tool can be used to manage a large ecosystem of runtimes and tools.
[src:common-lisp/getting-started] Steel Bank Common Lisp (SBCL) is available via the asdf-sbcl plugin.
[src:common-lisp/getting-started] You’ll find several ways of installation on its wiki (Debian package, Windows installer, Brew/Linux Brew,…).
[src:common-lisp/getting-started] Just launch the implementation executable on the command line to enter the REPL (Read Eval Print Loop), i.e. the interactive interpreter.
[src:common-lisp/getting-started] Quit with `(quit)` or `ctr-d` (on some implementations).
[src:common-lisp/getting-started] Here is a sample session: we start the `sbcl` binary, we see a startup message, we are landed in a Lisp prompt (the `*`), we enter a lisp form, then we quit.
[src:common-lisp/getting-started] You just evaluated Lisp code in a REPL, congratulations.
[src:common-lisp/getting-started] Of course, you’ll want to write code to a `.lisp` file.
[src:common-lisp/getting-started] Use `sbcl --load myfile.lisp` to load, compile and run this file.
[src:common-lisp/getting-started] After the top-level commands were run, the Lisp process doesn’t exit and it gives you a REPL, so you can keep working.
[src:common-lisp/getting-started] Once you edit your .lisp file, you don’t need to quit and call the SBCL command to `--load` your file again.
[src:common-lisp/getting-started] It’s the default Lisp prompt in a terminal.
[src:common-lisp/getting-started] In our editors, we usually see `CL-USER>`, denoting the current package.
[src:common-lisp/getting-started] Speaking of editors: of course, we can have a much more interactive workflow with a good editor setup.
[src:common-lisp/getting-started] The REPL is not very ergonomic out of the box, at least with SBCL: the arrow keys do not work in order to recall history (the previous commands entered), you don’t have completion of built-in Lisp functions, etc.
[src:common-lisp/getting-started] You can slightly enhance its functionality by installing and using `rlwrap`.
[src:common-lisp/getting-started] This brings *some* quality of life to a bare-bones terminal REPL, but we’ll setup our editor to offer a much better editing experience instead of working in such a terminal REPL.
[src:common-lisp/getting-started] The CLISP implementation has a better default REPL for the terminal (readline capabilities, completion of symbols).
[src:common-lisp/getting-started] to have error messages without the debugger.
[src:common-lisp/getting-started] It's handy to try things out, but we recommend to set-up your editor and to use SBCL or CCL.
[src:common-lisp/getting-started] switch to rlwrap, you can autocomplete file names.
[src:common-lisp/getting-started] ICL, Interactive Common Lisp, is an enhanced REPL for the terminal.
[src:common-lisp/getting-started] It works with any implementation you have on your system.
[src:common-lisp/getting-started] While it doesn’t replace a good editor, it can actually complement it.
[src:common-lisp/getting-started] Also note that ICL is beginner friendly.
[src:common-lisp/getting-started] It doesn’t have an interactive debugger.
[src:common-lisp/getting-started] Instead, it handles any error, prints the error message, and allows the programmer to see the backtrace with the `,bt` command.
[src:common-lisp/getting-started] You can install it with GNU/Linux pre-built binaries and packages (.deb, .rpm), on Windows with a zip, an exe or a MSI installer.
[src:common-lisp/getting-started] A similar project is `cl-repl`, see the editors section.
[src:common-lisp/getting-started] ICL is a project coded with the help of LLMs.
[src:common-lisp/getting-started] Lisp is interactive by nature, so in case of an error we enter the debugger.
[src:common-lisp/getting-started] This can be annoying in certain cases, so you might want to use SBCL’s `--disable-debugger` option.
[src:common-lisp/getting-started] Also, note that `icl` (see above) doesn’t have an interactive debugger, it prints the error message and allows you to print the backtrace.
[src:common-lisp/getting-started] Common Lisp has thousands of libraries available under a free software license.
[src:common-lisp/getting-started] Quicklisp is more than a package manager, it is also a central repository (a *dist*) that ensures that all libraries build together.
[src:common-lisp/getting-started] It provides a command-line tool, it works with project-local dependencies (read more below), it uses HTTPS by default and it is a repository independent from Quicklisp.
[src:common-lisp/getting-started] It provides its own *dist* but it is also possible to build our own.
[src:common-lisp/getting-started] This will create the `~/quicklisp/` directory, where Quicklisp will maintain its state and downloaded projects.
[src:common-lisp/getting-started] If you wish, you can install Quicklisp to a different location.
