[src:common-lisp/getting-started] Otherwise, you have to run `(load "~/quicklisp/setup.lisp")` in every session if you want to use Quicklisp or any of the libraries installed through it.
[src:common-lisp/getting-started] , section "Accessing symbols from a package".
[src:common-lisp/getting-started] We can install more than one library at once.
[src:common-lisp/getting-started] Anytime you want to use a third-party library in your Lisp REPL, you can run this `ql:quickload` command.
[src:common-lisp/getting-started] It will not hit the network a second time if it finds that the library is already installed on your file system.
[src:common-lisp/getting-started] Libraries are by default installed in `~/quicklisp/dists/quicklisp/`.
[src:common-lisp/getting-started] Note also that dozens of Common Lisp libraries are packaged in Debian.
[src:common-lisp/getting-started] The package names usually begin with the cl- prefix (use `apt-cache search --names-only "^cl-.*"` to list them all).
[src:common-lisp/getting-started] For example, in order to use the `cl-ppcre` library, one should first install the `cl-ppcre` package.
[src:common-lisp/getting-started] Here we pretend we don’t have Quicklisp installed and we use `require` to load a module that is available on the file system.
[src:common-lisp/getting-started] See Quicklisp’s documentation for more commands.
[src:common-lisp/getting-started] For instance, see how to upgrade or rollback your Quicklisp’s distribution.
[src:common-lisp/getting-started] A library installed here is automatically available for every project.
[src:common-lisp/getting-started] `*central-registry*` is a top-level variable inside the `asdf` package written with so-called “*earmuffs*”.
[src:common-lisp/getting-started] They are a useful convention, see the Variables chapter.
[src:common-lisp/getting-started] The practical difference between the two is that `ql:quickload` first tries to fetch the system from the Internet if it is not already installed.
[src:common-lisp/getting-started] Note that symlinks in local-projects to another location of your liking work too.
[src:common-lisp/getting-started] If we need libraries to be installed locally, for only one project, or in order to easily ship a list of dependencies with an application, we can use Qlot or ocicl.
[src:common-lisp/getting-started] Both projects provide a command-line tool, allow to pin dependencies in a lock file (`qlfile.lock` and `ocicl.csv`) and commands to install and manage dependencies locally, without touching your global Quicklisp installation (`qlot install`, `ocicl install`).
[src:common-lisp/getting-started] Of course you are recognizing the dependency management style that is predominant out there in other ecosystems: `npm`, `pip` etc.
[src:common-lisp/getting-started] However we are only presenting these tools now because they are far less needed in Common Lisp.
[src:common-lisp/getting-started] newcomers don't need to worry about project-local dependencies yet.
[src:common-lisp/getting-started] We can go a long way with global Quicklisp dependencies and quicklisp/local-projects/.
[src:common-lisp/getting-started] Choose the simplest tool for you (and it's surely Quicklisp).
[src:common-lisp/getting-started] The reasons are at least two fold: the language (and its implementations) is very stable, for example implementations *never* introduce breaking changes of *lisp syntax*.
[src:common-lisp/getting-started] They introduce minor breaking changes from time to time that only hardcore users will notice.
[src:common-lisp/getting-started] Second, the ecosystem is very stable too and usually *library authors play the game of stability*.
[src:common-lisp/getting-started] We saw deprecation warnings staying for 12 (twelve) years.
[src:common-lisp/getting-started] All in all, a newcomer in Common Lisp land doesn’t need to worry too much if at all about project-local dependencies.
[src:common-lisp/getting-started] Let’s mention another couple tools for the task.
[src:common-lisp/getting-started] Quicklisp also provides Quicklisp bundles.
[src:common-lisp/getting-started] They are self-contained sets of systems that are exported from Quicklisp and loadable without involving Quicklisp.
