[src:common-lisp/getting-started] You have created a new project, or you have an existing one, and you want to work with it in the REPL, but Quicklisp doesn’t know about it.
[src:common-lisp/getting-started] Well first, if you create it or clone it into one of `~/common-lisp`, `~/.local/share/common-lisp/source/` or `~/quicklisp/local-projects`, you’ll be able to `(ql:quickload …)` it with no further ado.
[src:common-lisp/getting-started] Otherwise you’ll need to compile and load its system definition (`.asd`) first.
[src:common-lisp/getting-started] In SLIME with the `slime-asdf` contrib loaded, type `C-c C-k` (*slime-compile-and-load-file*) in the `.asd`, then you can `(ql:quickload …)` it.
[src:common-lisp/getting-started] You can use `(asdf:load-asd "my-project.asd")` programmatically instead of `C-c C-k`.
[src:common-lisp/getting-started] Lastly, you can compile or eval the sources (`my-project.lisp`) with `C-c C-k` or `C-c C-c` (*slime-compile-defun*) in a form, and see its result in the REPL.
[src:common-lisp/getting-started] and since ASDF is integrated into Quicklisp, we can `quickload` our project right away.
[src:common-lisp/lisp-programming-language] Lisp was originally created as a practical mathematical notation for computer programs, influenced by (though not originally derived from) the notation of Alonzo Church's lambda calculus.
[src:common-lisp/lisp-programming-language] It quickly became a favored programming language for artificial intelligence (AI) research.
[src:common-lisp/lisp-programming-language] As one of the earliest programming languages, Lisp pioneered many ideas in computer science, including tree data structures, automatic storage management, dynamic typing, conditionals, higher-order functions, recursion, the self-hosting compiler, and the read–eval–print loop.
[src:common-lisp/lisp-programming-language] The name *LISP* derives from "List Processor".
[src:common-lisp/lisp-programming-language] Linked lists are one of Lisp's major data structures, and Lisp source code is made of lists.
[src:common-lisp/lisp-programming-language] Thus, Lisp programs can manipulate source code as a data structure, giving rise to the macro systems that allow programmers to create new syntax or new domain-specific languages embedded in Lisp.
[src:common-lisp/lisp-programming-language] The interchangeability of code and data gives Lisp its instantly recognizable syntax.
[src:common-lisp/lisp-programming-language] All program code is written as *s-expressions*, or parenthesized lists.
[src:common-lisp/lisp-programming-language] A function call or syntactic form is written as a list with the function or operator's name first, and the arguments following; for instance, a function `f` that takes three arguments would be called as `(f arg1 arg2 arg3)`.
[src:common-lisp/lisp-programming-language] John McCarthy began developing Lisp in 1958 while he was at the Massachusetts Institute of Technology (MIT).
[src:common-lisp/lisp-programming-language] Due to these factors, he consulted on the design of the Fortran List Processing Language, which was implemented as a Fortran library.
[src:common-lisp/lisp-programming-language] However, he was dissatisfied with it because it did not support recursion or a modern if-then-else statement (which was a new concept when Lisp was first introduced).
[src:common-lisp/lisp-programming-language] McCarthy's original notation used bracketed "M-expressions" that would be translated into S-expressions.
[src:common-lisp/lisp-programming-language] As an example, the M-expression `car[cons[A,B]]` is equivalent to the S-expression `(car (cons A B))`.
[src:common-lisp/lisp-programming-language] Once Lisp was implemented, programmers rapidly chose to use S-expressions, and M-expressions were abandoned.
[src:common-lisp/lisp-programming-language] M-expressions surfaced again with short-lived attempts of MLisp by Horace Enea and CGOL by Vaughan Pratt.
[src:common-lisp/lisp-programming-language] Lisp was first implemented by Steve Russell on an IBM 704 computer using punched cards.
[src:common-lisp/lisp-programming-language] Russell was working for McCarthy at the time and realized (to McCarthy's surprise) that the Lisp *eval* function could be implemented in machine code.
[src:common-lisp/lisp-programming-language] The result was a working Lisp interpreter which could be used to run Lisp programs, or more properly, "evaluate Lisp expressions".
[src:common-lisp/lisp-programming-language] Lisp dialects still use `car` and `cdr` (/kɑːr/ and /ˈkʊdər/) for the operations that return the first item in a list and the rest of the list, respectively.
[src:common-lisp/lisp-programming-language] McCarthy published Lisp's design in a paper in *Communications of the ACM* on April 1, 1960, entitled "Recursive Functions of Symbolic Expressions and Their Computation by Machine, Part I".
[src:common-lisp/lisp-programming-language] He showed that with a few simple operators and a notation for anonymous functions borrowed from Church, one can build a Turing-complete language for algorithms.
[src:common-lisp/lisp-programming-language] This compiler introduced the Lisp model of incremental compilation, in which compiled and interpreted functions can intermix freely.
[src:common-lisp/lisp-programming-language] The language used in Hart and Levin's memo is much closer to modern Lisp style than McCarthy's earlier code.
[src:common-lisp/lisp-programming-language] Garbage collection routines were developed by MIT graduate student Daniel Edwards, prior to 1962.
[src:common-lisp/lisp-programming-language] During the 1980s and 1990s, a great effort was made to unify the work on new Lisp dialects (mostly successors to Maclisp such as ZetaLisp and NIL (New Implementation of Lisp)) into a single language.
[src:common-lisp/lisp-programming-language] The new language, Common Lisp, was somewhat compatible with the dialects it replaced (the book *Common Lisp the Language* notes the compatibility of various constructs).
[src:common-lisp/lisp-programming-language] In 1994, ANSI published the Common Lisp standard, "ANSI X3.226-1994 Information Technology Programming Language Common Lisp".
[src:common-lisp/lisp-programming-language] Since its inception, Lisp was closely connected with the artificial intelligence research community, especially on PDP-10 systems.
[src:common-lisp/lisp-programming-language] Lisp was used as the implementation of the language Micro Planner, which was used in the famous AI system SHRDLU.
[src:common-lisp/lisp-programming-language] In the 1970s, as AI research spawned commercial offshoots, the performance of existing Lisp systems became a growing issue, as programmers needed to be familiar with the performance ramifications of the various techniques and choices involved in the implementation of Lisp.
[src:common-lisp/lisp-programming-language] Over its sixty-year history, Lisp has spawned many variations on the core theme of an S-expression language.
[src:common-lisp/lisp-programming-language] Some of these variations have been standardized and implemented by different groups with different priorities (for example, both Common Lisp and Scheme have multiple implementations).
[src:common-lisp/lisp-programming-language] However, in other cases a software project defines a Lisp without a standard and there is no clear distinction between the dialect and the implementation (for example, Clojure and Emacs Lisp fall into this category).
[src:common-lisp/lisp-programming-language] Differences between dialects (and/or implementations) may be quite visible—for instance, Common Lisp uses the keyword `defun` to name a function, but Scheme uses `define`.
[src:common-lisp/lisp-programming-language] Within a dialect that is standardized conforming implementations support the same core language, but with different extensions and libraries.
[src:common-lisp/lisp-programming-language] This sometimes also creates quite visible changes from the base language - for instance, Guile (an implementation of Scheme) uses `define*` to create functions which can have default arguments and/or keyword arguments, neither of which are standardized.
[src:common-lisp/lisp-programming-language] After having declined somewhat in the 1990s, Lisp has experienced a resurgence of interest after 2000.
[src:common-lisp/lisp-programming-language] Most new activity has been focused around implementations of Common Lisp, Scheme, Emacs Lisp, Clojure, and Racket, and includes development of new portable libraries and applications.
[src:common-lisp/lisp-programming-language] Many new Lisp programmers were inspired by writers such as Paul Graham and Eric S.
[src:common-lisp/lisp-programming-language] Raymond to pursue a language others considered antiquated.
[src:common-lisp/lisp-programming-language] New Lisp programmers often describe the language as an eye-opening experience and claim to be substantially more productive than in other languages.
[src:common-lisp/lisp-programming-language] This increase in awareness may be contrasted to the "AI winter" and Lisp's brief gain in the mid-1990s.
[src:common-lisp/lisp-programming-language] As of 2010, there were eleven actively maintained Common Lisp implementations.
[src:common-lisp/lisp-programming-language] *Common-lisp.net* is a hosting site for open source Common Lisp projects.
[src:common-lisp/lisp-programming-language] Quicklisp is a library manager for Common Lisp.
[src:common-lisp/lisp-programming-language] Fifty years of Lisp (1958–2008) was celebrated at LISP50@OOPSLA.
[src:common-lisp/lisp-programming-language] There are regular local user meetings in Boston, Vancouver, and Hamburg.
[src:common-lisp/lisp-programming-language] Other events include the European Common Lisp Meeting, the European Lisp Symposium and an International Lisp Conference.
[src:common-lisp/lisp-programming-language] The Scheme community actively maintains over twenty implementations.
[src:common-lisp/lisp-programming-language] Several significant new implementations (Chicken, Gambit, Gauche, Ikarus, Larceny, Ypsilon) have been developed in the 2000s (decade).
[src:common-lisp/lisp-programming-language] The Revised5 Report on the Algorithmic Language Scheme standard of Scheme was widely accepted in the Scheme community.
[src:common-lisp/lisp-programming-language] The Scheme Requests for Implementation process has created a lot of quasi-standard libraries and extensions for Scheme.
[src:common-lisp/lisp-programming-language] User communities of individual Scheme implementations continue to grow.
[src:common-lisp/lisp-programming-language] A new language standardization process was started in 2003 and led to the R6RS Scheme standard in 2007.
[src:common-lisp/lisp-programming-language] Academic use of Scheme for teaching computer science seems to have declined somewhat.
[src:common-lisp/lisp-programming-language] Some universities are no longer using Scheme in their computer science introductory courses; MIT now uses Python instead of Scheme for its undergraduate computer science program and MITx massive open online course.
[src:common-lisp/lisp-programming-language] There are several new dialects of Lisp: Arc, Hy, Nu, Liskell, and LFE (Lisp Flavored Erlang).
[src:common-lisp/lisp-programming-language] The parser for Julia is implemented in Femtolisp, a dialect of Scheme (Julia is inspired by Scheme, which in turn is a Lisp dialect).
[src:common-lisp/lisp-programming-language] Common Lisp and Scheme represent two major streams of Lisp development.
[src:common-lisp/lisp-programming-language] These languages embody significantly different design choices.
[src:common-lisp/lisp-programming-language] The primary influences were Lisp Machine Lisp, Maclisp, NIL, S-1 Lisp, Spice Lisp, and Scheme.
[src:common-lisp/lisp-programming-language] It has many of the features of Lisp Machine Lisp (a large Lisp dialect used to program Lisp Machines), but was designed to be efficiently implementable on any personal computer or workstation.
[src:common-lisp/lisp-programming-language] Common Lisp is a general-purpose programming language and thus has a large language standard including many built-in data types, functions, macros and other language elements, and an object system (Common Lisp Object System).
[src:common-lisp/lisp-programming-language] Common Lisp also borrowed certain features from Scheme such as lexical scoping and lexical closures.
[src:common-lisp/lisp-programming-language] Common Lisp implementations are available for targeting different platforms such as the LLVM, the Java virtual machine, x86-64, PowerPC, Alpha, ARM, Motorola 68000, and MIPS, and operating systems such as Windows, macOS, Linux, Solaris, FreeBSD, NetBSD, OpenBSD, Dragonfly BSD, and Heroku.
[src:common-lisp/lisp-programming-language] Scheme is a statically scoped and properly tail-recursive dialect of the Lisp programming language invented by Guy L.
[src:common-lisp/lisp-programming-language] It was designed to have exceptionally clear and simple semantics and few different ways to form expressions.
[src:common-lisp/lisp-programming-language] Designed about a decade earlier than Common Lisp, Scheme is a more minimalist design.
[src:common-lisp/lisp-programming-language] It has a much smaller set of standard features but with certain implementation features (such as tail-call optimization and full continuations) not specified in Common Lisp.
[src:common-lisp/lisp-programming-language] A wide variety of programming paradigms, including imperative, functional, and message passing styles, find convenient expression in Scheme.
[src:common-lisp/lisp-programming-language] Scheme continues to evolve with a series of standards (Revisedn Report on the Algorithmic Language Scheme) and a series of Scheme Requests for Implementation.
[src:common-lisp/lisp-programming-language] Clojure is a dialect of Lisp that targets mainly the Java virtual machine, and the Common Language Runtime (CLR), the Python VM, the Ruby VM YARV, and compiling to JavaScript.
[src:common-lisp/lisp-programming-language] It is designed to be a pragmatic general-purpose language.
[src:common-lisp/lisp-programming-language] Clojure draws considerable influences from Haskell and places a very strong emphasis on immutability.
[src:common-lisp/lisp-programming-language] Clojure provides access to Java frameworks and libraries, with optional type hints and type inference, so that calls to Java can avoid reflection and enable fast primitive operations.
[src:common-lisp/lisp-programming-language] Clojure is not designed to be backwards compatible with other Lisp dialects.
[src:common-lisp/lisp-programming-language] Further, Lisp dialects are used as scripting languages in many applications, with the best-known being Emacs Lisp in the Emacs editor, AutoLISP and later Visual Lisp in AutoCAD, Nyquist in Audacity, and Scheme in LilyPond.
[src:common-lisp/lisp-programming-language] The potential small size of a useful Scheme interpreter makes it particularly popular for embedded scripting.
[src:common-lisp/lisp-programming-language] Examples include SIOD and TinyScheme, both of which have been successfully embedded in the GIMP image processor under the generic name "Script-fu".
[src:common-lisp/lisp-programming-language] LIBREP, a Lisp interpreter by John Harper originally based on the Emacs Lisp language, has been embedded in the Sawfish window manager.
[src:common-lisp/lisp-programming-language] Lisp has officially standardized dialects: R6RS Scheme, R7RS Scheme, IEEE Scheme, ANSI Common Lisp and ISO ISLISP.
[src:common-lisp/lisp-programming-language] Lisp was the first language where the structure of program code is represented faithfully and directly in a standard data structure—a quality much later dubbed "homoiconicity".
[src:common-lisp/lisp-programming-language] Thus, Lisp functions can be manipulated, altered or even created within a Lisp program without lower-level manipulations.
[src:common-lisp/lisp-programming-language] This is generally considered one of the main advantages of the language with regard to its expressive power, and makes the language suitable for syntactic macros and meta-circular evaluation.
[src:common-lisp/lisp-programming-language] A conditional using an *if–then–else* syntax was invented by McCarthy for a chess program written in Fortran.
[src:common-lisp/lisp-programming-language] He proposed its inclusion in ALGOL, but it was not made part of the Algol 58 specification.
[src:common-lisp/lisp-programming-language] For Lisp, McCarthy used the more general *cond*-structure.
[src:common-lisp/lisp-programming-language] Algol 60 took up *if–then–else* and popularized it.
[src:common-lisp/lisp-programming-language] Lisp deeply influenced Alan Kay, the leader of the research team that developed Smalltalk at Xerox PARC; and in turn Lisp was influenced by Smalltalk, with later dialects adopting object-oriented programming features (inheritance classes, encapsulating instances, message passing, etc.) in the 1970s.
[src:common-lisp/lisp-programming-language] The Flavors object system introduced the concept of multiple inheritance and the mixin.
[src:common-lisp/lisp-programming-language] The Common Lisp Object System provides multiple inheritance, multimethods with multiple dispatch, and first-class generic functions, yielding a flexible and powerful form of dynamic dispatch.
[src:common-lisp/lisp-programming-language] Many years later, Alan Kay suggested that as a result of the confluence of these features, only Smalltalk and Lisp could be regarded as properly conceived object-oriented programming systems.
[src:common-lisp/lisp-programming-language] Lisp introduced the concept of automatic garbage collection, in which the system walks the heap looking for unused memory.
[src:common-lisp/lisp-programming-language] Progress in modern sophisticated garbage collection algorithms such as generational garbage collection was stimulated by its use in Lisp.
[src:common-lisp/lisp-programming-language] Largely because of its resource requirements with respect to early computing hardware (including early microprocessors), Lisp did not become as popular outside of the AI community as Fortran and the ALGOL-descended C language.
[src:common-lisp/lisp-programming-language] Because of its suitability to complex and dynamic applications, Lisp enjoyed some resurgence of popular interest in the 2010s.
[src:common-lisp/lisp-programming-language] Lisp is an expression oriented language.
[src:common-lisp/lisp-programming-language] Unlike most other languages, no distinction is made between "expressions" and "statements"; all code and data are written as expressions.
[src:common-lisp/lisp-programming-language] When an expression is *evaluated*, it produces a value (possibly multiple values), which can then be embedded into other expressions.
[src:common-lisp/lisp-programming-language] McCarthy's 1958 paper introduced two types of syntax: *Symbolic expressions* (S-expressions, sexps), which mirror the internal representation of code and data; and *Meta expressions* (M-expressions), which express functions of S-expressions.
[src:common-lisp/lisp-programming-language] M-expressions never found favor, and almost all Lisps today use S-expressions to manipulate both code and data.
[src:common-lisp/lisp-programming-language] The use of parentheses is Lisp's most immediately obvious difference from other programming language families.
[src:common-lisp/lisp-programming-language] As a result, students have long given Lisp nicknames such as *Lost In Stupid Parentheses*, or *Lots of Irritating Superfluous Parentheses*.
[src:common-lisp/lisp-programming-language] However, the S-expression syntax is also responsible for much of Lisp's power: the syntax is simple and consistent, which facilitates manipulation by computer.
[src:common-lisp/lisp-programming-language] However, the syntax of Lisp is not limited to traditional parentheses notation.
[src:common-lisp/lisp-programming-language] It can be extended to include alternative notations.
[src:common-lisp/lisp-programming-language] For example, XMLisp is a Common Lisp extension that employs the metaobject protocol to integrate S-expressions with the Extensible Markup Language (XML).
[src:common-lisp/lisp-programming-language] The reliance on expressions gives the language great flexibility.
[src:common-lisp/lisp-programming-language] Because Lisp functions are written as lists, they can be processed exactly like data.
[src:common-lisp/lisp-programming-language] This allows easy writing of programs which manipulate other programs (metaprogramming).
[src:common-lisp/lisp-programming-language] Many Lisp dialects exploit this feature using macro systems, which enables extension of the language almost without limit.
[src:common-lisp/lisp-programming-language] A Lisp list is written with its elements separated by whitespace, and surrounded by parentheses.
[src:common-lisp/lisp-programming-language] For example, `(1 2 foo)` is a list whose elements are the three *atoms* `1`, `2`, and `foo`.
[src:common-lisp/lisp-programming-language] These values are implicitly typed: they are respectively two integers and a Lisp-specific data type called a "symbol", and do not have to be declared as such.
[src:common-lisp/lisp-programming-language] The empty list `()` is also represented as the special atom `nil`.
[src:common-lisp/lisp-programming-language] This is the only entity in Lisp which is both an atom and a list.
[src:common-lisp/lisp-programming-language] Expressions are written as lists, using prefix notation.
[src:common-lisp/lisp-programming-language] The first element in the list is the name of a function, the name of a macro, a lambda expression or the name of a "special operator" (see below).
[src:common-lisp/lisp-programming-language] The remainder of the list are the arguments.
[src:common-lisp/lisp-programming-language] The "quote" before the `foo` in the preceding example is a "special operator" which returns its argument without evaluating it.
[src:common-lisp/lisp-programming-language] Any unquoted expressions are recursively evaluated before the enclosing expression is evaluated.
[src:common-lisp/lisp-programming-language] The third argument is a list; lists can be nested.
[src:common-lisp/lisp-programming-language] Arithmetic operators are treated similarly.
[src:common-lisp/lisp-programming-language] The equivalent under infix notation would be "`1 + 2 + 3 + 4`".
[src:common-lisp/lisp-programming-language] Lisp has no notion of operators as implemented in ALGOL-derived languages.
[src:common-lisp/lisp-programming-language] Arithmetic operators in Lisp are variadic functions (or *n-ary*), able to take any number of arguments.
[src:common-lisp/lisp-programming-language] equivalent to `(setq x (+ x 1))`, returning the new value of `x`.
[src:common-lisp/lisp-programming-language] "Special operators" (sometimes called "special forms") provide Lisp's control structure.
[src:common-lisp/lisp-programming-language] For example, the special operator `if` takes three arguments.
[src:common-lisp/lisp-programming-language] If the first argument is non-nil, it evaluates to the second argument; otherwise, it evaluates to the third argument.
[src:common-lisp/lisp-programming-language] Of course, this would be more useful if a non-trivial expression had been substituted in place of `nil`.
[src:common-lisp/lisp-programming-language] Lisp also provides logical operators **and**, **or** and **not**.
[src:common-lisp/lisp-programming-language] The **and** and **or** operators do short-circuit evaluation and will return their first nil and non-nil argument respectively.
[src:common-lisp/lisp-programming-language] Another special operator, `lambda`, is used to bind variables to values which are then evaluated within an expression.
[src:common-lisp/lisp-programming-language] This operator is also used to create functions: the arguments to `lambda` are a list of arguments, and the expression or expressions to which the function evaluates (the returned value is the value of the last expression that is evaluated).
[src:common-lisp/lisp-programming-language] evaluates to a function that, when applied, takes one argument, binds it to `arg` and returns the number one greater than that argument.
[src:common-lisp/lisp-programming-language] Lambda expressions are treated no differently from named functions; they are invoked the same way.
[src:common-lisp/lisp-programming-language] Here, we're doing a function application: we execute the anonymous function by passing to it the value 5.
[src:common-lisp/lisp-programming-language] Named functions are created by storing a lambda expression in a symbol using the defun macro.
[src:common-lisp/lisp-programming-language] `(defun f (a) b...)` defines a new function named `f` in the global environment.
[src:common-lisp/lisp-programming-language] where `setf` is a macro used to set the value of the first argument `fdefinition 'f` to a new function object.
[src:common-lisp/lisp-programming-language] `fdefinition` is a global function definition for the function named `f`.
[src:common-lisp/lisp-programming-language] `#'` is an abbreviation for `function` special operator, returning a function object.
[src:common-lisp/lisp-programming-language] In the original **LISP** there were two fundamental data types: atoms and lists.
[src:common-lisp/lisp-programming-language] A list was a finite ordered sequence of elements, where each element is either an atom or a list, and an atom was a number or a symbol.
[src:common-lisp/lisp-programming-language] A symbol was essentially a unique named item, written as an alphanumeric string in source code, and used either as a variable name or as a data item in symbolic processing.
[src:common-lisp/lisp-programming-language] For example, the list `(FOO (BAR 1) 2)` contains three elements: the symbol `FOO`, the list `(BAR 1)`, and the number 2.
[src:common-lisp/lisp-programming-language] The essential difference between atoms and lists was that atoms were immutable and unique.
[src:common-lisp/lisp-programming-language] Two atoms that appeared in different places in source code but were written in exactly the same way represented the same object, whereas each list was a separate object that could be altered independently of other lists and could be distinguished from other lists by comparison operators.
[src:common-lisp/lisp-programming-language] As more data types were introduced in later Lisp dialects, and programming styles evolved, the concept of an atom lost importance.
[src:common-lisp/lisp-programming-language] Many dialects still retained the predicate *atom* for legacy compatibility, defining it true for any object which is not a cons.
[src:common-lisp/lisp-programming-language] A Lisp list is implemented as a singly linked list.
[src:common-lisp/lisp-programming-language] Each cell of this list is called a *cons* (in Scheme, a *pair*) and is composed of two pointers, called the *car* and *cdr*.
[src:common-lisp/lisp-programming-language] These are respectively equivalent to the `data` and `next` fields discussed in the article *linked list*.
[src:common-lisp/lisp-programming-language] Of the many data structures that can be built out of cons cells, one of the most basic is called a *proper list*.
[src:common-lisp/lisp-programming-language] A proper list is either the special `nil` (empty list) symbol, or a cons in which the `car` points to a datum (which may be another cons structure, such as a list), and the `cdr` points to another proper list.
[src:common-lisp/lisp-programming-language] If a given cons is taken to be the head of a linked list, then its car points to the first element of the list, and its cdr points to the rest of the list.
[src:common-lisp/lisp-programming-language] For this reason, the `car` and `cdr` functions are also called `first` and `rest` when referring to conses which are part of a linked list (rather than, say, a tree).
[src:common-lisp/lisp-programming-language] Thus, a Lisp list is not an atomic object, as an instance of a container class in C++ or Java would be.
[src:common-lisp/lisp-programming-language] A list is nothing more than an aggregate of linked conses.
[src:common-lisp/lisp-programming-language] A variable that refers to a given list is simply a pointer to the first cons in the list.
[src:common-lisp/lisp-programming-language] Traversal of a list can be done by *cdring down* the list; that is, taking successive cdrs to visit each cons of the list; or by using any of several higher-order functions to map a function over a list.
[src:common-lisp/lisp-programming-language] Because conses and lists are so universal in Lisp systems, it is a common misconception that they are Lisp's only data structures.
[src:common-lisp/lisp-programming-language] In fact, all but the most simplistic Lisps have other data structures, such as vectors (arrays), hash tables, structures, and so forth.
[src:common-lisp/lisp-programming-language] Parenthesized S-expressions represent linked list structures.
[src:common-lisp/lisp-programming-language] There are several ways to represent the same list as an S-expression.
[src:common-lisp/lisp-programming-language] A cons can be written in *dotted-pair notation* as `(a . b)`, where `a` is the car and `b` the cdr.
[src:common-lisp/lisp-programming-language] A longer proper list might be written `(a .
[src:common-lisp/lisp-programming-language] This is conventionally abbreviated as `(a b c d)` in *list notation*.
[src:common-lisp/lisp-programming-language] An improper list may be written in a combination of the two – as `(a b c . d)` for the list of three conses whose last cdr is `d` (i.e., the list `(a .
[src:common-lisp/lisp-programming-language] Lisp provides many built-in procedures for accessing and controlling lists.
[src:common-lisp/lisp-programming-language] Lists can be created directly with the `list` procedure, which takes any number of arguments, and returns the list of these arguments.
[src:common-lisp/lisp-programming-language] Because of the way that lists are constructed from cons pairs, the `cons` procedure can be used to add an element to the front of a list.
[src:common-lisp/lisp-programming-language] The `cons` procedure is asymmetric in how it handles list arguments, because of how lists are constructed.
[src:common-lisp/lisp-programming-language] The `append` procedure appends two (or more) lists to one another.
[src:common-lisp/lisp-programming-language] Lisp lists, being simple linked lists, can share structure with one another.
[src:common-lisp/lisp-programming-language] That is to say, two lists can have the same *tail*, or final sequence of conses.
[src:common-lisp/lisp-programming-language] the lists `foo` and `bar` are `(a b c)` and `(x b c)` respectively.
[src:common-lisp/lisp-programming-language] However, the tail `(b c)` is the same structure in both lists.
[src:common-lisp/lisp-programming-language] It is not a copy; the cons cells pointing to `b` and `c` are in the same memory locations for both lists.
[src:common-lisp/lisp-programming-language] Sharing structure rather than copying can give a dramatic performance improvement.
[src:common-lisp/lisp-programming-language] However, this technique can interact in undesired ways with functions that alter lists passed to them as arguments.
[src:common-lisp/lisp-programming-language] This changes `foo` to `(a b goose)`, but thereby also changes `bar` to `(x b goose)` – a possibly unexpected result.
[src:common-lisp/lisp-programming-language] This can be a source of bugs, and functions which alter their arguments are documented as *destructive* for this very reason.
[src:common-lisp/lisp-programming-language] Aficionados of functional programming avoid destructive functions.
[src:common-lisp/lisp-programming-language] In the Scheme dialect, which favors the functional style, the names of destructive functions are marked with a cautionary exclamation point, or "bang"—such as `set-car!` (read *set car bang*), which replaces the car of a cons.
[src:common-lisp/lisp-programming-language] In the Common Lisp dialect, destructive functions are commonplace; the equivalent of `set-car!` is named `rplaca` for "replace car".
[src:common-lisp/lisp-programming-language] This function is rarely seen, however, as Common Lisp includes a special facility, `setf`, to make it easier to define and use destructive functions.
[src:common-lisp/lisp-programming-language] A frequent style in Common Lisp is to write code functionally (without destructive calls) when prototyping, then to add destructive calls as an optimization where it is safe to do so.
[src:common-lisp/lisp-programming-language] Lisp evaluates expressions which are entered by the user.
[src:common-lisp/lisp-programming-language] Symbols and lists evaluate to some other (usually, simpler) expression – for instance, a symbol evaluates to the value of the variable it names; `(+ 2 3)` evaluates to `5`.
[src:common-lisp/lisp-programming-language] However, most other forms evaluate to themselves: if entering `5` into Lisp, it returns `5`.
[src:common-lisp/lisp-programming-language] Any expression can also be marked to prevent it from being evaluated (as is necessary for symbols and lists).
[src:common-lisp/lisp-programming-language] This is the role of the `quote` special operator, or its abbreviation `'` (one quotation mark).
[src:common-lisp/lisp-programming-language] For instance, usually if entering the symbol `foo`, it returns the value of the corresponding variable (or an error, if there is no such variable).
[src:common-lisp/lisp-programming-language] To refer to the literal symbol, enter `(quote foo)` or, usually, `'foo`.
[src:common-lisp/lisp-programming-language] Both Common Lisp and Scheme also support the *backquote* operator (termed *quasiquote* in Scheme), entered with the ` character (Backtick).
[src:common-lisp/lisp-programming-language] This is almost the same as the plain quote, except it allows expressions to be evaluated and their values interpolated into a quoted list with the comma `,` *unquote* and comma-at `,@` *splice* operators.
[src:common-lisp/lisp-programming-language] If the variable `snue` has the value `(bar baz)` then `(foo ,snue) evaluates to `(foo (bar baz))`, while `(foo ,@snue) evaluates to `(foo bar baz)`.
[src:common-lisp/lisp-programming-language] The backquote is most often used in defining macro expansions.
[src:common-lisp/lisp-programming-language] Self-evaluating forms and quoted forms are Lisp's equivalent of literals.
[src:common-lisp/lisp-programming-language] It may be possible to modify the values of (mutable) literals in program code.
[src:common-lisp/lisp-programming-language] For instance, if a function returns a quoted form, and the code that calls the function modifies the form, this may alter the behavior of the function on subsequent invocations.
[src:common-lisp/lisp-programming-language] Modifying a quoted form like this is generally considered bad style, and is defined by ANSI Common Lisp as erroneous (resulting in "undefined" behavior in compiled files, because the file-compiler can coalesce similar constants, put them in write-protected memory, etc.).
[src:common-lisp/lisp-programming-language] Lisp's formalization of quotation has been noted by Douglas Hofstadter (in *Gödel, Escher, Bach*) and others as an example of the philosophical idea of self-reference.
[src:common-lisp/lisp-programming-language] The Lisp family splits over the use of dynamic or static (a.k.a. lexical) scope.
[src:common-lisp/lisp-programming-language] Clojure, Common Lisp and Scheme make use of static scoping by default, while newLISP, Picolisp and the embedded languages in Emacs and AutoCAD use dynamic scoping.
[src:common-lisp/lisp-programming-language] Since version 24.1, Emacs uses both dynamic and lexical scoping.
[src:common-lisp/lisp-programming-language] A fundamental distinction between Lisp and other languages is that in Lisp, the textual representation of a program is simply a human-readable description of the same internal data structures (linked lists, symbols, number, characters, etc.) as would be used by the underlying Lisp system.
[src:common-lisp/lisp-programming-language] Lisp uses this to implement a very powerful macro system.
[src:common-lisp/lisp-programming-language] Like other macro languages such as the one defined by the C preprocessor (the macro preprocessor for the C, Objective-C and C++ programming languages), a macro returns code that can then be compiled.
[src:common-lisp/lisp-programming-language] However, unlike C preprocessor macros, the macros are Lisp functions and so can exploit the full power of Lisp.
[src:common-lisp/lisp-programming-language] Further, because Lisp code has the same structure as lists, macros can be built with any of the list-processing functions in the language.
[src:common-lisp/lisp-programming-language] In short, anything that Lisp can do to a data structure, Lisp macros can do to code.
[src:common-lisp/lisp-programming-language] In contrast, in most other languages, the parser's output is purely internal to the language implementation and cannot be manipulated by the programmer.
[src:common-lisp/lisp-programming-language] This feature makes it easy to develop *efficient* languages within languages.
[src:common-lisp/lisp-programming-language] For example, the Common Lisp Object System can be implemented cleanly as a language extension using macros.
[src:common-lisp/lisp-programming-language] This means that if an application needs a different inheritance mechanism, it can use a different object system.
[src:common-lisp/lisp-programming-language] This is in stark contrast to most other languages; for example, Java does not support multiple inheritance and there is no reasonable way to add it.
[src:common-lisp/lisp-programming-language] In simplistic Lisp implementations, this list structure is directly interpreted to run the program; a function is literally a piece of list structure which is traversed by the interpreter in executing it.
[src:common-lisp/lisp-programming-language] However, most substantial Lisp systems also include a compiler.
[src:common-lisp/lisp-programming-language] The compiler translates list structure into machine code or bytecode for execution.
[src:common-lisp/lisp-programming-language] This code can run as fast as code compiled in conventional languages such as C.
[src:common-lisp/lisp-programming-language] Macros expand before the compilation step, and thus offer some interesting options.
[src:common-lisp/lisp-programming-language] If a program needs a precomputed table, then a macro might create the table at compile time, so the compiler need only output the table and need not call code to create the table at run time.
[src:common-lisp/lisp-programming-language] Some Lisp implementations even have a mechanism, `eval-when`, that allows code to be present during compile time (when a macro would need it), but not present in the emitted module.
[src:common-lisp/lisp-programming-language] Lisp languages are often used with an interactive command line, which may be combined with an integrated development environment (IDE).
[src:common-lisp/lisp-programming-language] The user types in expressions at the command line, or directs the IDE to transmit them to the Lisp system.
[src:common-lisp/lisp-programming-language] Lisp *reads* the entered expressions, *evaluates* them, and *prints* the result.
[src:common-lisp/lisp-programming-language] For this reason, the Lisp command line is called a *read–eval–print loop* (REPL).
[src:common-lisp/lisp-programming-language] The basic operation of the REPL is as follows.
[src:common-lisp/lisp-programming-language] This is a simplistic description which omits many elements of a real Lisp, such as quoting and macros.
[src:common-lisp/lisp-programming-language] The `read` function accepts textual S-expressions as input, and parses them into an internal data structure.
[src:common-lisp/lisp-programming-language] For instance, if you type the text `(+ 1 2)` at the prompt, `read` translates this into a linked list with three elements: the symbol `+`, the number 1, and the number 2.
[src:common-lisp/lisp-programming-language] It so happens that this list is also a valid piece of Lisp code; that is, it can be evaluated.
[src:common-lisp/lisp-programming-language] This is because the car of the list names a function—the addition operation.
[src:common-lisp/lisp-programming-language] A `foo` will be read as a single symbol.
[src:common-lisp/lisp-programming-language] `123` will be read as the number one hundred and twenty-three.
[src:common-lisp/lisp-programming-language] The `eval` function evaluates the data, returning zero or more other Lisp data as a result.
[src:common-lisp/lisp-programming-language] Evaluation does not have to mean interpretation; some Lisp systems compile every expression to native machine code.
[src:common-lisp/lisp-programming-language] It is simple, however, to describe evaluation as interpretation: To evaluate a list whose car names a function, `eval` first evaluates each of the arguments given in its cdr, then applies the function to the arguments.
[src:common-lisp/lisp-programming-language] In this case, the function is addition, and applying it to the argument list `(1 2)` yields the answer `3`.
[src:common-lisp/lisp-programming-language] The symbol `foo` evaluates to the value of the symbol foo.
[src:common-lisp/lisp-programming-language] Data like the string "123" evaluates to the same string.
[src:common-lisp/lisp-programming-language] The list `(quote (1 2 3))` evaluates to the list (1 2 3).
[src:common-lisp/lisp-programming-language] It is the job of the `print` function to represent output to the user.
[src:common-lisp/lisp-programming-language] For a simple result such as `3` this is trivial.
[src:common-lisp/lisp-programming-language] An expression which evaluated to a piece of list structure would require that `print` traverse the list and print it out as an S-expression.
[src:common-lisp/lisp-programming-language] To implement a Lisp REPL, it is necessary only to implement these three functions and an infinite-loop function.
[src:common-lisp/lisp-programming-language] (Naturally, the implementation of `eval` will be complex, since it must also implement all special operators like `if` or `lambda`.) This done, a basic REPL is one line of code: `(loop (print (eval (read))))`.
[src:common-lisp/lisp-programming-language] The Lisp REPL typically also provides input editing, an input history, error handling and an interface to the debugger.
[src:common-lisp/lisp-programming-language] In Common Lisp, arguments are evaluated in applicative order ('leftmost innermost'), while in Scheme order of arguments is undefined, leaving room for optimization by a compiler.
[src:common-lisp/lisp-programming-language] Lisp originally had very few control structures, but many more were added during the language's evolution.
[src:common-lisp/lisp-programming-language] Programmers in the Scheme dialect often express loops using tail recursion.
[src:common-lisp/lisp-programming-language] Scheme's commonality in academic computer science has led some students to believe that tail recursion is the only, or the most common, way to write iterations in Lisp, but this is incorrect.
[src:common-lisp/lisp-programming-language] All oft-seen Lisp dialects have imperative-style iteration constructs, from Scheme's `do` loop to Common Lisp's complex `loop` expressions.
[src:common-lisp/lisp-programming-language] By contrast, ANSI Common Lisp does not require the optimization commonly termed a tail call elimination.
[src:common-lisp/lisp-programming-language] Some Lisp control structures are *special operators*, equivalent to other languages' syntactic keywords.
[src:common-lisp/lisp-programming-language] Expressions using these operators have the same surface appearance as function calls, but differ in that the arguments are not necessarily evaluated—or, in the case of an iteration expression, may be evaluated more than once.
[src:common-lisp/lisp-programming-language] In contrast to most other major programming languages, Lisp allows implementing control structures using the language.
[src:common-lisp/lisp-programming-language] Several control structures are implemented as Lisp macros, and can even be macro-expanded by the programmer who wants to know how they work.
[src:common-lisp/lisp-programming-language] Both Common Lisp and Scheme have operators for non-local control flow.
[src:common-lisp/lisp-programming-language] The differences in these operators are some of the deepest differences between the two dialects.
[src:common-lisp/lisp-programming-language] Scheme supports *re-entrant continuations* using the `call/cc` procedure, which allows a program to save (and later restore) a particular place in execution.
